an></p><p><span class=\"post_date\">February 27, 2013 8:19 a.m.</span><br/><strong><a  href=\"http://www.statcan.gc.ca/daily-quotidien/130227/dq130227b-eng.htm\"><span class=\"post_title\">International travel account, fourth quarter 2012</span></a></strong><br />\r\n<span class=\"post_author\"></span>\r\n<br/><span class=\"post_body\">(<a  href=\"http://course.downes.ca/feed/37\">Statistics Canada, The Daily</a>) Canada\'s international travel deficit with the world increased by $49 million to $4.6 billion during the fourth quarter. While the travel deficit with overseas countries narrowed during this period, this was more than offset by a growing deficit with the United States.</span></p><p><span class=\"post_date\">February 27, 2013 8:19 a.m.</span><br/><strong><a  href=\"http://www.statcan.gc.ca/daily-quotidien/130227/dq130227c-eng.htm\"><span class=\"post_title\">Railway carloadings, December 2012</span></a></strong><br />\r\n<span class=\"post_author\"></span>\r\n<br/><span class=\"post_body\">(<a  href=\"http://course.downes.ca/feed/37\">Statistics Canada, The Daily</a>) Canadian railways carried 26.0 million tonnes of freight in December, up 0.7% from December 2011. Freight loaded domestically as well as traffic received from United States connections both rose during the month, with the United States traffic providing the strongest growth.</span></p>\r\n<div><span style=\"float:right;\"><p><a  href=\"http://course.downes.ca/economy.htm\">Read More: Business and Economy</a></p></span></div>\r\n</section>\r\n\r\n<section id=\"entertainment\">\r\n<div class=\"section\"><p>\r\n<h2>Entertainment</h2>\r\n<p><span class=\"post_date\">February 27, 2013 6:24 a.m.</span><br/><strong><a  href=\"http://musicnerd.ca/spend-an-evening-with-the-tenors/\"><span class=\"post_title\">Spend An Evening With The Tenors</span></a></strong><br />\r\n<span class=\"post_author\"><a  href=\"http://course.downes.ca/author/215\">Ken Kelley</a></span>\r\n<br/><span class=\"post_body\">(